      Many organizations use a centralized authentication server to manage user identities and enforce consistent security policies across multiple applications. This approach simplifies logout management and improves overall security posture.

      So, which strategy is best? It depends on your specific needs and constraints. Token blacklisting provides immediate logout but introduces state. Short-lived tokens reduce the window of vulnerability but require frequent refresh. Refresh token rotation mitigates the impact of compromised refresh tokens but adds complexity. And a centralized authentication server simplifies management but can introduce performance bottlenecks.

      Next up, we'll look at how to handle token storage and transmission securely.

